The paper deals with random graphs and their geometric embeddings, which are topics commonly studied in the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) and Computational Geometry (cs.CG) sub-categories. The use of weights and distances in the graph also suggests that the paper may fall under the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. The study of the stretch factor, which is a measure of the distortion of distances in the embedded graph, is a topic of interest in the Graph Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on analyzing the asymptotic behavior of the stretch factor suggests that it may also be relevant to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
